SIMPLE: hare
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hare
<hw>Hare</hw> <pr>(h⟦acir⟧r)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Cf.
<er>Harry</er>, <er>Harass</er>.]</ety> <def>To excite; to tease,
harass, or worry; to harry.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Locke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hare</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hare
<hw>Hare</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>hara</ets>; akin to D.
<ets>haas</ets>, G. <ets>hase</ets>, OHG. <ets>haso</ets>, Dan. & Sw.
<ets>hare</ets>, Icel. <ets>h⟦emac⟧ri</ets>, Skr.
<ets>⟦cced⟧a⟦cced⟧a</ets>. ⟦root⟧226.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A rodent of the genus
<gen>Lepus</gen>, having long hind legs, a short tail, and a divided
upper lip. It is a timid animal, moves swiftly by leaps, and is
remarkable for its fecundity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The species of hares are numerous. The common European
hare is <spn>Lepus timidus</spn>. The northern or varying hare of
America (<spn>Lepus Americanus</spn>), and the prairie hare (<spn>Lepus
campestris</spn>), turn white in winter. In America, the various species
of hares are commonly called <altname>rabbits</altname>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>A small constellation situated
south of and under the foot of Orion; Lepus.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Hare and hounds</b></col>, <cd>a game played by men and
boys, two, called <xex>hares</xex>, having a few minutes' start, and
scattering bits of paper to indicate their course, being chased by the
others, called the <xex>hounds</xex>, through a wide circuit.</cd> --
<col><b>Hare kangaroo</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a small
Australian kangaroo (<spn>Lagorchestes Leporoides</spn>), resembling the
hare in size and color,</cd> -- <col><b>Hare's lettuce</b></col>
<fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a plant of the genus <gen>Sonchus</gen>, or sow
thistle; -- so called because hares are said to eat it when fainting
with heat.</cd> <au>Dr. Prior.</au> -- <col><b>Jumping hare</b></col>.
<fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>See under <er>Jumping</er>.</cd> --
<mcol><col><b>Little chief hare</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Crying
hare</b></col></mcol>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>See <er>Chief
hare</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Sea hare</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld>
<cd>See <er>Aplysia</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Harebell</ent>⟦br⟧
